dataset_description.json.Name: Route Learning
Funding: National Institutes of Health Grant (1RO1NS089729) to B.A.K
dataset_description.json.Acknowledgements: We thank Anthony Stigliani and Kalanit Grill-Spector for providing stimuli for the category localizer. This work was supported by a grant from the National Institutes of Health (1RO1NS089729) to B.A.K.
dataset_description.json.HowToAcknowledge: This data was obtained from the OpenfMRI database. Its accession number is ds000217

task-localizer_bold.json.Instructions: Participants were instructed to fixate on a red dot in the center of a screen and press a button everytime a scrambled picture appeared on screen.
task-localizer_bold.json.TaskDescription: The localizer scan contained 36 alternating blocks of three image types (12 blocks per category): faces, scenes (hallways or houses), and objects (cars or guitars). Each block lasted a total of 6 s and contained 12 greyscale images presented for 500 ms each. Subjects pressed a button whenever they detected a scrambled image, which occurred on half of all blocks (counterbalanced across category). An additional 12 baseline ‘blocks’ showing a blank grey screen (also 6 s each) were randomly interspersed with the other blocks.

task-picturetest_beh.json.Instructions: Participants were shown images selected from the route and were instructed to select the destination label associated with each image
task-picturetest_beh.json.TaskDescription: : After exiting the scanner subjects completed an extended picture test which included ten pictures drawn from each route (every 10th picture from picture 4 to 94), tested in random order. On each trial, the route picture was presented above the set of destination names (4 destination names in Experiment 1 and 2 destination names in Experiment 2). Subjects used a computer mouse to click on the destination name associated with each picture. This test was self-paced.

route_number.Description: The route-unique number. In each experiment two sets of routes were used across participants. Group 1 subjects learned routes 1-4 and Group 2 subjects learned routes 5-8. See participant list for each subjects group number.

segment.Description: The segment number of each route to which the picture belonged. Each route contained an initial segment that was shared with another route (Segment 1), and a later segment, including the destination, that was route-specific (Segment 2).

Levels.1: Pictures in the route that occured before or during the third turn in the route.
Levels.2: Pictures in the route that occured after the third turn in the route.

response.Description: The participants selection of the destination for that trial

response_time.Description: Participants response time. Participants had unlimited time to respond.

response_type.Description: Responses on each trial were categorized based on the subjects destination choice.

Levels.competitor: selection of the overlapping route's destination
Levels.other: selection of one of the non-overlapping routes' destinations.

hits.Description: Binary value representing wether the participant correctly selected the route's destination

task-routelearning_bold.json.Instructions: Participants were instructed to learn to predict the destination of each route and how to get there.
task-routelearning_bold.json.TaskDescription: On route learning trials participants passively viewed the routes. Within each run there were two catch trials during which the route would stop at a predetermined picture number and participants would be asked either to select the destination of the route (Destination Trials) or the next turn in the route (Direction Trials). These trials were dropped from all analyses. Each experiment contained two sets of routes that were counterbalances across subjects. The route group each participants was in can be found in the participants file. In Experiment 1 routes were divided into overlapping pairs (route-group 1: routes 1/2 and 3/4 or route-group 2: 5/6 and 7/8) and non-overlapping routes (route-group 1: routes 1/3, 1/4, 2/3, and 2,4 or route-group 2: 5/7, 5/8, 6/7, and 6/8). Experiment 2 also contained route pairs that were non-overlapping but ended in the same destination. In this experiment overlapping pairs were the same as Experiment 1 (route-group 3: routes 1/2 and 3/4 or route-group 4: 5/6 and 7/8), non-overlapping pairs were (route-group 3 : 1/4 and 2/3 or route-group 2: 5/8 and 6/7) and the same-destination routes were (route-group 3 : 1/3 and 2/4 or route-group 2: 5/7 and 6/8)

Levels.study_trial: On study trials participants viewed the route in full
Levels.catch_trial: Catch trials were instereted to ensure participants were paying actively learning. On catch trials the route would stop at a given picture number (see test_picture) and participants would be tested on the route (see test_type)

route_number.Description: The route-unique number. In each experiment two sets of routes were used across participants. Group 1 subjects learned routes 1-4 and Group 2 subjects learned routes 5-8. See participant list for each subjects group number.

test_type.Description: On catch trials subjects were tested about the destination of the route or the direction of the next turn.

Levels.direction: On direction test trials participants selected the direction of the upcoming turn (left or right)
Levels.destination: On destination test trials participants selected the destination name of the current route

test_picture.Description: For catch trial this value represents the picture number in the route on which the trial stopped for the test.

test_response.Description: Participants response to the catch trial.

test_RT.Description: Participants response time to the catch trial. If blank participants did not respond

test_correct.Description: Binary value representing wether the participant correctly answered the catch trial quesiton
